  "prompt": "How did British political traditions affect the formation of the American government?",
  "response": "British political traditions significantly influenced the formation of the American government in several key ways:\n\n1. Constitutional Principles\n- Magna Carta (1215) introduced the concept of limited government and individual rights\n- English Bill of Rights (1689) established parliamentary supremacy and individual liberties\n- These documents influenced the U.S. Constitution and Bill of Rights\n\n2. Separation of Powers\n- The British system of checks and balances between monarchy, parliament, and courts\n- Inspired the American model of separating executive, legislative, and judicial branches\n\n3. Representative Government\n- Parliamentary system of elected representatives\n- Influenced the creation of Congress and representative democracy in the United States\n\n4. Common Law\n- American legal system adopted British common law principles\n- Established precedent-based legal reasoning\n\n5. Individual Rights\n- British traditions of personal liberty and protection from arbitrary government power\n- Directly influenced the U.S. Bill of Rights\n\n6. Federal Structure\n- British colonial governance model\n- Inspired the concept of federalism with power distributed between national and state governments\n\n7. Electoral Processes\n- Parliamentary election procedures\n- Influenced American voting and election systems\n\nWhile the Americans rejected monarchy, they adapted many British political traditions to create a republican system of government that preserved core principles of individual liberty and representative governance.",
